The Maurist edition was several times reprinted, the best-known reprint being that of Gaume (Paris, 1836). Goldbaeher’s edition began to appear in 1895, after twenty- two years of preparati0n3 in the Vienna Corpus Serip- torum Eeel. Latinorum it forms vols. 34 (parts 1 and 2, containing Epp. i.-xxx. and xxxi-cxxiii„ 1895, 1898), 44 (part 3, Epp. cxxiv.-clxxxiv., 1904) and 57 (Epp. clxxv.-CCIXX., 1911). The final volume, containing pre- faces and indices, was not issued until 1923, fifty years after the editor had begun his long task.

Meanwhile, the original eorpus of 270 letters had been increased by several fortunate, if meagre, discoveries.
